  <!--
    Suppression 1: Flask / Werkzeug debugger pin CVE
    ============================================================
    CVE:        CVE-2024-34069
    Component:  Werkzeug (Flask dependency)
    Rationale:  The debugger is NEVER enabled in NeuroSphere production or
                staging environments. All Flask services run with
                FLASK_ENV=production and debug=False enforced via Helm values
                and Kubernetes ConfigMaps. The vulnerable code path (debugger
                PIN bypass) is unreachable in our deployment.
    Evidence:   - Helm values: services.*.flask.debug = false
                - K8s admission policy blocks FLASK_DEBUG=1
                - Verified by penetration test report Q1-2026 §4.2
    Reviewed:   2026-06-01 by Security Engineering
    Next Review: 2026-09-01
  -->
  <suppress>
    <notes><![CDATA[
      False positive: Werkzeug debugger is disabled in all deployed environments.
      The debugger PIN bypass vulnerability (CVE-2024-34069) requires the
      interactive debugger to be enabled, which is blocked by admission policy.
      Reviewed 2026-06-01 — next review 2026-09-01.
    ]]></notes>
    <cve>CVE-2024-34069</cve>
  </suppress>

  <!--
    Suppression 2: gRPC C-core denial-of-service via HPACK
    ============================================================
    CVE:        CVE-2023-44487  (HTTP/2 Rapid Reset)
    Component:  grpcio
    Rationale:  NeuroSphere gRPC services sit behind an Envoy sidecar proxy
                (Istio service mesh) that enforces per-stream rate limits and
                MAX_CONCURRENT_STREAMS=100. The Envoy version deployed
                (1.29+) includes the upstream mitigation. Direct pod-to-pod
                gRPC traffic is restricted by NetworkPolicy to same-namespace
                only, limiting attack surface to authenticated internal callers.
    Evidence:   - Istio mesh config: meshConfig.h2UpgradePolicy = UPGRADE
                - Envoy stream limit: envoy.resource_limits.max_connections = 1024
                - NetworkPolicy audit report Q2-2026
    Reviewed:   2026-05-15 by Platform Security
    Next Review: 2026-08-15
  -->
  <suppress>
    <notes><![CDATA[
      Mitigated at infrastructure layer: Envoy sidecar enforces HTTP/2 stream
      limits and rate limiting. Direct gRPC exposure is blocked by NetworkPolicy.
      CVE-2023-44487 rapid reset attack is not exploitable in our mesh topology.
      Reviewed 2026-05-15 — next review 2026-08-15.
    ]]></notes>
    <cve>CVE-2023-44487</cve>
  </suppress>

  <!--
    Suppression 3: Protobuf Python DoS via deeply nested messages
    ============================================================
    CVE:        CVE-2024-7254
    Component:  protobuf (google-protobuf Python package)
    Rationale:  NeuroSphere protocol buffer schemas are strictly defined with
                a maximum nesting depth of 4 levels (validated by buf lint).
                All inbound protobuf payloads are processed through a custom
                deserialization wrapper (neurosphere.common.proto_utils) that
                enforces a recursion limit of 50 (default is 100). Untrusted
                external input never reaches protobuf deserialization directly;
                all external APIs are REST/JSON with schema validation.
    Evidence:   - buf.yaml: lint rules include MESSAGE_NESTING_DEPTH <= 4
                - proto_utils.py: RecursionLimit(50) decorator
                - API gateway validates JSON schema before conversion
    Reviewed:   2026-06-10 by Application Security
    Next Review: 2026-09-10
  -->
  <suppress>
    <notes><![CDATA[
      False positive for our usage: protobuf messages have enforced nesting
      limits via buf lint and runtime recursion guards. External input is
      JSON-validated before protobuf conversion.
      CVE-2024-7254 requires crafted deeply nested messages which our schema
      constraints prevent.
      Reviewed 2026-06-10 — next review 2026-09-10.
    ]]></notes>
    <cve>CVE-2024-7254</cve>
  </suppress>

  <!--
    Suppression 4: NumPy buffer overflow in array deserialization
    ============================================================
    CVE:        CVE-2024-5642
    Component:  numpy
    Rationale:  The CVE affects numpy.load() with allow_pickle=True on
                untrusted .npy files. NeuroSphere's telemetry-ingest and
                diagnostic-processor services use numpy only for in-memory
                numerical computation on validated sensor data arrays.
                We never call numpy.load() on user-supplied files; all data
                ingestion goes through our validated protobuf pipeline.
                allow_pickle is globally disabled via numpy configuration.
    Evidence:   - Bandit scan confirms no numpy.load(allow_pickle=True) calls
                - Code review checklist item SEC-NP-001
                - numpy.set_printoptions / config enforced in service entrypoint
    Reviewed:   2026-06-05 by Data Engineering Security
    Next Review: 2026-09-05
  -->
  <suppress>
    <notes><![CDATA[
      Not exploitable: numpy.load() with untrusted input is not used in
      NeuroSphere services. All numerical data arrives via validated protobuf
      streams. allow_pickle is globally disabled.
      CVE-2024-5642 requires loading crafted .npy files which our architecture
      does not permit.
      Reviewed 2026-06-05 — next review 2026-09-05.
    ]]></notes>
    <cve>CVE-2024-5642</cve>
  </suppress>

</suppressions>
